# Environment Setup Instructions

## Create `.env.local` File

Create a file named `.env.local` in the root of your project (same level as `package.json`):

```
e:\hello_leads\salesflow-hub\.env.local
```

## Copy This Content

```env
# Supabase Configuration
VITE_SUPABASE_URL=https://uvqlonqtlqypxqatgbih.supabase.co
VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=sb_publishable_A8iz_SOWHx_G5eKQZGgfMg_csYrQ5Q8

# Optional: Add more config later
# VITE_API_URL=http://localhost:3000
```

## .gitignore Update

Make sure `.env.local` is in your `.gitignore` (it should be by default):

```
.env.local
.env.*.local
```

## Verify Setup

After creating `.env.local`:

1. Restart your dev server: `npm run dev`
2. The Supabase client will automatically use these variables
3. Check browser console for any errors

## Access Variables in Code

In your React components:

```typescript
// This is optional - the code already has hardcoded values
const url = import.meta.env.VITE_SUPABASE_URL;
const key = import.meta.env.VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY;
```

## File Structure

```
salesflow-hub/
├── src/
├── node_modules/
├── .env.local          ← Create this file
├── package.json
├── vite.config.ts
└── ...
```

## Installation Command

```bash
npm install @supabase/supabase-js
```

## Verify Installation

After installing, check that the package is in `package.json`:

```json
"dependencies": {
  "@supabase/supabase-js": "^2.x.x",
  ...
}
```

---

Done! Your environment is now configured for Supabase.
